Dravet syndrome occurs when the <em><a href="https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/SCN1A" target="_blank">SCN1A</a></em> gene is not working correctly.&nbsp;DNA changes known as <a href="https://www.cancer.gov/publications/dictionaries/genetics-dictionary/def/genetic-variant " target="_blank">pathogenic variants</a> are responsible for making genes work incorrectly or sometimes, not at all.[15702]&nbsp;<br />
<br />
DNA changes in the <em><a href="https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/SCN1B" target="_blank">SCN1B</a></em>, <em><a href="https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/GABRG2" target="_blank">GABRG2</a></em>, <em><a href="https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/SCN2A" target="_blank">SCN2A</a></em> and several other genes are associated with seizure disorders with similar symptoms to Dravet syndrome.[15703]&nbsp;
